Collecting USA Data

This excel files were downloaded from the FRED database of economical and financial data from USA. [ADD DESCRIPTION OF THE DATA, SEARCH IF FROM THE FRED WEBSITE] ### Important notes: + The CPI is an index, to compute the annualized inflation rate, we need to compute (cpi_t12/cpi_0), since we have monthly data. + The interest rate is already annnualized

# https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/FEDFUNDS for description
cpi_us = read_excel('raw_data/CPIAUCSL.xls', skip = 10)
interest_rate_us = read_excel('raw_data/FEDFUNDS.xls', skip = 10)
cpi_us <- cpi_us %>%
  mutate(inflation_rate_annual =  CPIAUCSL/lag(CPIAUCSL, 12)-1 )# %>% LATER WHEN WE DECIDE TO COMPUTE THE CHANGE
  #mutate(change_inflation = (inflation_rate_annual-lag(inflation_rate_annual)))

inflation_rate_us <- cpi_us[c('observation_date', 'inflation_rate_annual')]

#Merge both databases
data_us <- merge(interest_rate_us, inflation_rate_us,by="observation_date")
colnames(data_us) <- c('observation_date', 'interest_us', 'inflation_us')

data_us$interest_us <- data_us$interest_us/100

head(data_us)

Collecting Brazil Data

We will collect the CDI from Brazil as an proxy of the interest rate, and the IPCA which is a proxy of the Brazillian CPI. We will use a library to help us collect the data from the BCB API.

library('GetBCBData') 

#IPCA its brazillian CPI
brazil_cpi <- GetBCBData::gbcbd_get_series(
id = 433)

Fetching id = 433 [433] from BCB-SGS with cache 
     Found 120 observations
# overnight rate in brazil annulized (base 252)
brazil_interest_rate <- GetBCBData::gbcbd_get_series(
id = 4389)

Fetching id = 4389 [4389] from BCB-SGS with cache 
     Found 2512 observations
# TO ANNUALIZE THE DATA
brazil_cpi$value <- (brazil_cpi$value/100+1)^12-1
brazil_interest_rate$value <- brazil_interest_rate$value/100


data_br <- merge(brazil_cpi[c('ref.date','value')], brazil_interest_rate[c('ref.date','value')],by="ref.date")
colnames(data_br) <- c('observation_date', 'brazil_cpi', 'brazil_interest_rate')

head(data_br)

Boxplot Data

labels <- c(
  replicate(length(data_us$interest_us), 'Interest USA'),
  replicate(length(data_us$inflation_us), 'Inflation USA'),
  replicate(length(data_br$interest_br), 'Interest BR'),
  replicate(length(data_br$inflation_br), 'Inflation BR')
)

values <- c(
  data_us$interest_us, 
  data_us$inflation_us,
  data_br$interest_br,
  data_br$inflation_br
)

country <- c(
  replicate(length(data_us$interest_us)*2, 'USA'),
  replicate(length(data_br$interest_br)*2, 'Brazil')
)

boxplot_data <- data.frame(
  value =  values,
  category = labels,
  Country = country
)

head(boxplot_data)

ggplot(boxplot_data, aes(x=category, y=value, fill = Country)) +
  geom_boxplot() + 
  labs(
    y = 'Annualized Rate',
    x = 'Category',
    title = 'Destribution of Interest and Inflation Rates by Country'
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)

Analyzing Relation between change in Interest Rate over Interest Rates

# To create the inflation rate in pp%
  #cpi <- cpi %>%
   # mutate(inflation_rate_annual =  CPIAUCSL/lag(CPIAUCSL, 12)-1 )# %>% LATER WHEN WE DECIDE TO COMPUTE THE CHANGE
    #mutate(change_inflation = (inflation_rate_annual-lag(inflation_rate_annual)))
delta_us <- data_us %>% 
  mutate(change_inflation_us = inflation_us-lag(inflation_us, 1)) %>%
  mutate(change_interest_us = interest_us-lag(interest_us, 1))

delta_br <- data_br %>% 
  mutate(change_inflation_br = inflation_brazil-lag(inflation_brazil, 1)) %>%
  mutate(change_interest_br = interest_brazil-lag(interest_brazil, 1))

ggplot(data = delta_us, aes(x=change_interest_us, y=change_inflation_us)) +
  geom_hex()
